StepBegin(n=99)
ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think='There are two issues with the BDD tests:\n\n1. **Matching step defini
tion files fail with `ReferenceError: then is not defined`**: In `matching-commo
n.js`, I defined `aliasThenAnd` at the module level, outside the exported functi
on, where `then` and `and` are not defined. I need to move `aliasThenAnd` inside
the exported function.\n\n2. **Auth tests fail because `bdd-setup.js` now includ
es `MatchingModule` which requires `DataSource`**: The `MatchingService` injects
`DataSource` directly, but in the TestingModule, I added `{ provide: DataSource,
useValue: mockDataSource }` in the providers array. However, NestJS can\'t resol
ve it for `MatchingModule` because `MatchingModule` imports `TypeOrmModule.forFe
ature([...])` but the `DataSource` provider is only in the root module\'s provid
ers list.\n\nThe issue is that when `MatchingModule` is imported into the Testin
gModule, NestJS tries to resolve `DataSource` for `MatchingService` within `Matc
hingModule`\'s context. Since `DataSource` is only provided at the root level of
the TestingModule, it should be accessible. But wait - `TypeOrmModule.forFeature
` creates providers that need `DataSource` from `TypeOrmModule`. If we\'re overr
iding the repository tokens, that shouldn\'t be an issue.\n\nActually, looking a
t the error more carefully: "Nest can\'t resolve dependencies of the MatchingSer
vice (UserProfileEntityRepository, MatchActionEntityRepository, MatchEntityRepos
itory, ConversationEntityRepository, ConversationParticipantEntityRepository, ?)
. Please make sure that the argument DataSource at index [5] is available in the
MatchingModule context."\n\nThis means `MatchingService` constructor has 6 param
eters: 5 repository tokens and `DataSource`. The repository tokens are overridde
n at the root TestingModule level, which should work. But `DataSource` is also p
rovided at the root level.\n\nWait, in `bdd-setup.js`, `DataSource` is imported 
from `typeorm` and provided in the TestingModule. But `MatchingModule` might be 
importing `TypeOrmModule.forRoot` or something else that creates a separate cont
ext.\n\nActually, looking at `matching.module.ts`:\n```typescript\n@Module({\n  
imports: [\n    TypeOrmModule.forFeature([\n      UserProfileEntity,\n      Matc
hActionEntity,\n      MatchEntity,\n      ConversationEntity,\n      Conversatio
nParticipantEntity,\n    ]),\n  ],\n  controllers: [MatchingController, MatchesC
ontroller],\n  providers: [MatchingService, MatchingGateway],\n  exports: [Match
ingService, MatchingGateway],\n})\nexport class MatchingModule {}\n```\n\nWhen `
MatchingModule` is imported into the TestingModule, `TypeOrmModule.forFeature([.
..])` tries to create repository providers. These providers need `DataSource` or
`Connection`. Since we override the repository tokens at the root level, those s
hould be used. But `MatchingService` itself needs `DataSource`.\n\nThe `DataSour
ce` token in NestJS TypeORM is a special injection token. When we do `{ provide:
DataSource, useValue: mockDataSource }`, it should be available. But maybe the i
mported `DataSource` from `typeorm` doesn\'t match the token that NestJS TypeORM
uses.\n\nWait, looking at the original `bdd-setup.js`:\n```javascript\nconst typ
eorm = require(\'../../../apps/api/node_modules/typeorm\');\nconst DataSource = 
typeorm.DataSource;\n```\n\nAnd then:\n```javascript\n{ provide: DataSource, use
Value: mockDataSource },\n```\n\nThis worked before for `ProfileService`. But `P
rofileService` might not inject `DataSource` directly. `MatchingService` does in
ject `DataSource` directly.\n\nThe issue might be that `MatchingModule` imports 
`TypeOrmModule.forFeature([...])` which creates a new scope or provider that sha
dows the root `DataSource`. Or the `DataSource` class from `typeorm` isn\'t the 
same token that `@nestjs/typeorm` uses internally.\n\nActually, in NestJS TypeOR
M, the `DataSource` token is exported from `@nestjs/typeorm` as `getDataSourceTo
ken()` or similar. But using the `DataSource` class directly as a token should w
ork if `@nestjs/typeorm` also uses it.\n\nWait, looking at the error: "argument 
DataSource at index [5] is available in the MatchingModule context". This means 
the other 5 dependencies (repositories) were resolved successfully because we ov
errode them. But `DataSource` wasn\'t.\n\nIn NestJS TypeORM v10+, the internal t
oken for DataSource might be different. Let me check what `@nestjs/typeorm` expo
rts.\n\nActually, I think the simplest fix is to NOT import `MatchingModule` in 
`bdd-setup.js`, but instead manually configure the MatchingController and Matchi
ngService in the TestingModule, similar to how ProfileService and ProfileControl
ler are configured.\n\nLet me revert `bdd-setup.js` to NOT import `MatchingModul
e`, and instead just add `MatchingController`, `MatchingService`, and `MatchingG
ateway` directly to the TestingModule with the necessary overrides.\n\nThis way,
we avoid `TypeOrmModule.forFeature` inside `MatchingModule` creating its own pro
viders that might conflict.\n\nLet me rewrite `bdd-setup.js` to remove `Matching
Module` import and instead set up matching components manually.\n\nActually, wai
t. `MatchingModule` exports `MatchingService` and `MatchingGateway`. If I don\'t
import `MatchingModule`, I need to provide `MatchingService` and `MatchingGatewa
y` directly, along with their dependencies.\n\n`MatchingService` needs:\n- `getR
epositoryToken(UserProfileEntity)` -> mockProfileRepo\n- `getRepositoryToken(Mat
chActionEntity)` -> mockMatchActionRepo\n- `getRepositoryToken(MatchEntity)` -> 
