    type='think',
    think='Let me think about this more carefully. The BDD setup requires compil
ed dist files. If the API isn\'t built, we can\'t run the BDD tests anyway. But 
the review asks for real step implementations.\n\nLooking at the auth step defin
ition pattern, `auth-common.js` has the step implementations and imports `getSer
ver` from `auth-helpers.js` which wraps `bdd-setup.js`. The auth `.steps.js` fil
es import `auth-common.js`.\n\nFor matching, I should create a `matching-common.
js` with real implementations. But I need the matching server to be available in
`bdd-setup.js`.\n\nGiven the complexity and that the API needs to be built for B
DD tests to work anyway, let me:\n1. Extend `bdd-setup.js` to include MatchingMo
dule and matching mock repos\n2. Create `matching-common.js` with real step impl
ementations\n3. Update each matching `.steps.js` to use `matching-common.js`\n\n
But wait - the matching `.steps.js` files currently use `autoBindSteps(feature, 
[commonSteps])`. `autoBindSteps` automatically matches step definitions from `co
mmonSteps` to the feature file steps. `commonSteps` is from `common.js`.\n\nIf I
create `matching-common.js`, I should have the `.steps.js` files use `defineFeat
ure` with `matching-common.js` instead of `autoBindSteps`.\n\nLet me look at how
`autoBindSteps` works vs `defineFeature`. `autoBindSteps` takes an array of step
definition objects and auto-binds them. `defineFeature` takes a callback that de
fines each test manually.\n\nFor better control and clearer test structure, I\'l
l use `defineFeature` in each `.steps.js` file, similar to `auth_login_phone_num
ber_login.steps.js`.\n\nBut this requires writing a lot of code. Let me think ab
out what\'s most important.\n\nActually, looking at the review again: "为每个 sc
enario 编写真实的步骤实现". This means real implementations for each scenario.\n
\nLet me create a comprehensive `matching-common.js` that provides the step defi
nitions, and update the `.steps.js` files to use it properly.\n\nFor the server 
setup, I\'ll modify `bdd-setup.js` to include MatchingModule. I need to be caref
ul about not breaking auth tests.\n\nActually, I think there\'s a simpler approa
ch. Instead of modifying the shared `bdd-setup.js`, I can create a `matching-bdd
-setup.js` that creates its own server. But that duplicates a lot of code.\n\nOr
, I can create a helper function in `bdd-setup.js` that\'s extensible.\n\nWait, 
looking at the auth tests again: `auth-common.js` imports `getServer` from `auth
-helpers.js` which re-exports from `bdd-setup.js`. The server is cached globally
. So once created, it\'s reused.\n\nFor matching tests, if I modify `bdd-setup.j
s` to also include MatchingModule, the auth tests will still work because Matchi
ngModule just adds more routes and doesn\'t interfere.\n\nLet me modify `bdd-set
up.js` to add MatchingModule support.\n\nActually, let me look at this from a di
fferent angle. The review says BDD tests are empty. The most important thing is 
to provide real step implementations. Even if the BDD server setup isn\'t perfec
t, having real test logic is the primary requirement.\n\nLet me write `matching-
common.js` that reuses `getServer` but also sets up matching-specific mocks. I\'
ll modify `bdd-setup.js` minimally.\n\nActually, you know what, let me take a pr
agmatic approach. I\'ll:\n1. Modify `bdd-setup.js` to include MatchingModule and
matching repos\n2. Create `matching-common.js` with all matching step definition
s\n3. Update each `.steps.js` to import and use `matching-common.js`\n\nLet me d
o this.\n\nFor `bdd-setup.js`, I need to add:\n- Imports for MatchingModule, Mat
chingController, MatchingService\n- Imports for MatchActionEntity, MatchEntity, 
ConversationEntity, ConversationParticipantEntity\n- Mock repos for these entiti
es\n- Add MatchingController to controllers\n- Add MatchingService to providers\
n- Override the new repository tokens\n- Return the new mock repos\n\nLet me wri
te the modifications carefully.',
