ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think='OK, there are two issues:\n\n1. **Step matching with `{string}` and `
{int}`**: `defineFeature` expects the step pattern to use regex when matching qu
oted strings or integers. The error messages show:\n   - `given(/^the user sees 
a card for target user "(.*)"$/, (arg0) => {`\n   - `then(/^a match record shoul
d be created with status "(.*)"$/, (arg0) => {`\n   - `and(/^the app should show
an empty state "(.*)"$/, (arg0) => {`\n\n   So I need to use regex patterns for 
these steps instead of `{string}`.\n\n2. **Match list test failure**: `item.nick
name` is an empty string `""`, not a truthy value. This is because the `profileR
epo.findOne` mock returns `{ nickname: \'Bob\', ... }` but the actual mock imple
mentation might not be working correctly. Looking at the mock, when `opts.where.
user_id === \'bob\'`, it returns the profile. But maybe the `where` check isn\'t
matching because `findOne` is called differently.\n\n   Wait, looking at `matchi
ng-helpers.js`:\n   ```javascript\n   profileRepo.findOne.mockImplementation((op
ts) => {\n     if (opts.where.user_id === \'bob\') {\n   ```\n\n   But in `getMa
tches` in `matching.service.ts`:\n   ```typescript\n   const otherProfile = awai
t this.profileRepo.findOne({\n     where: { user_id: otherUserId },\n   });\n   
```\n\n   This should work. But the assertion says `item.nickname` is `""`. Look
ing at `matching.service.ts` line 419:\n   ```typescript\n   nickname: otherProf
ile?.nickname || "",\n   ```\n\n   If `otherProfile` is null or `nickname` is un
defined, it returns `""`. So `findOne` must be returning null.\n\n   Why? Maybe 
because `opts.where` in the mock is `{ user_id: \'bob\' }` but the mock is recei
ving a different structure.\n\n   Actually, in TypeORM, `findOne({ where: { user
_id: \'bob\' } })` passes the whole object as the first argument. So `opts.where
.user_id` should be `\'bob\'`.\n\n   Wait, but looking at the mock setup in `mat
ching-helpers.js`, I set up `matchRepo.createQueryBuilder` to return matches. Bu
t the `getMatches` method iterates over `sliced` matches and calls `profileRepo.
findOne` for each. The mock should return the correct profile.\n\n   Hmm, but in
`bdd-setup.js`, `profileRepo` is shared with auth tests and is a single mock obj
ect. When auth tests run before matching tests, they might have changed the mock
implementation. And `jest.clearAllMocks()` clears call history but doesn\'t rese
